Strategy for dealing with missing values

  • Although 22% of the price values are missing, it is too risky to impute values for price because price is the response variable in the model. We’ll therefore ignore the observations with missing prices.

  • Need to find a way to impute values for number of bedrooms and bathrooms (~20% of the data is missing - quite large)

Focus <- Focus %>% 
  filter(!is.na(Price))

We will use the mean imputation method to impute the missing data in Bathroom and Bedroom2 because the k-nearest neighbours method results in the program not having enough memory to compute the data.

# Using the mean imputation method to impute missing data in Bathroom and Bedroom2 variables for each house type
fh <- bind_shadow(Focus) %>% 
  filter(Type=="h") %>%
  mutate(Bedroom2= ifelse(is.na(Bedroom2), 
                             mean(Bedroom2, na.rm=TRUE),
                             Bedroom2),
         Bathroom = ifelse(is.na(Bathroom), 
                             mean(Bathroom, na.rm=TRUE),
                             Bathroom)) 

ft <- bind_shadow(Focus) %>% 
  filter(Type=="t") %>%
  mutate(Bedroom2 = ifelse(is.na(Bedroom2), 
                             mean(Bedroom2, na.rm=TRUE),
                             Bedroom2),
         Bathroom = ifelse(is.na(Bathroom), 
                             mean(Bathroom, na.rm=TRUE),
                             Bathroom))

fu <- bind_shadow(Focus) %>% 
  filter(Type=="u") %>%
  mutate(Bedroom2 = ifelse(is.na(Bedroom2), 
                             mean(Bedroom2, na.rm=TRUE),
                             Bedroom2),
         Bathroom = ifelse(is.na(Bathroom), 
                             mean(Bathroom, na.rm=TRUE),
                             Bathroom))
 
Focus_shadow <- bind_rows(fh, ft, fu)

# Rounding imputations for Bedroom2 and Bathroom to nearest whole number 
round_df <- function(x, digits) {
    # round all numeric variables
    # x: data frame 
    # digits: number of digits to round
    numeric_columns <- sapply(x, mode) == 'numeric'
    x[numeric_columns] <-  round(x[numeric_columns], digits)
    x
}

Focus_shadow <- Focus_shadow %>%
  mutate(Bedroom2 = round_df(Focus_shadow$Bedroom2, 0),
         Bathroom = round_df(Focus_shadow$Bathroom, 0))

# Plotting the imputed values against missing values
ggplot(Focus_shadow,
       aes(x = Bedroom2,
           y = Bathroom, 
           colour=Bathroom_NA)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.7) + 
  facet_wrap(~Type) + 
  scale_colour_brewer(palette="Dark2")

From here, we can see a somewhat weak positive relationship between the number of rooms and house price. It appears to be somewhat normally distributed, barring the more extreme values of homes with more than 10 rooms. This seems to make sense, as the more rooms a house has, the more likely it is to be of higher quality. Perhaps when the number of rooms increases too high, the quality of the house decreases, resulting in a lower price.

Building the model, explaining your choices of transformations, variable selection, interactions

Transformations

  • Since ordered factors are treated as “numeric” in the default model fit, we will convert Type to be an unordered categorical variable.
  • Since Distance is heavily skewed, we take the logarithm of it to remove this effect.
  • We will look at the observations that have less than 10 rooms to remove the effect of the outliers with this variable.
Focus_complete <- Focus_complete %>%
  mutate(Type_c = factor(Type, ordered = FALSE)) %>%
  mutate(Distance_log = log10(Distance)) %>%
  filter(Rooms <= 10) %>%
  filter(Distance_log != -Inf)

From previous, we notice that there is a strong relationship between the number of rooms and the number of bedrooms and bathrooms. Thus, the model incorporates this interaction, along with the effect of the house’s distance from the CBD and type of house it is. Upon discussion, we thought that the number of rooms and the distance from the CBD are the most important factors in determining house price, so we weighted these more heavily in our model by squaring the figures.

library(broom)
focus_fit <- lm(Price~ I(Rooms^2) * Bedroom2* Bathroom * Type_c * + I(Distance_log^2) * Type_c+ Type_c * Rooms * Distance_log, data =Focus_complete)
glance(focus_fit)
##   r.squared adj.r.squared    sigma statistic p.value df    logLik      AIC
